1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:19,000
This is David Cline for the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Civil Rights History Project.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:27,000
Today is March 1, 2013, and I'm in San Mateo, California.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
And today we have the pleasure of speaking with Mildred Pitts Walter Good afternoon.

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:33,000
Good afternoon.

7
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Thank you so much for participating in this project. We really, really appreciate it.

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Thank you for inviting me to participate.

9
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,000
So we're going to I'm on just for the record, I'm on channel 2.

10
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
I'm Miss Walters on channel 1.

11
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Okay.

12
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
And we'll just start right into it.

13
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Okay. So what I'd like you, if we could just start, if you could tell me a little bit about where you are raised and your family.

14
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
I was born in Louisiana in 1922.

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:11,000
And my mother and father were together for a while.

16
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:22,000
And when Long-Bell Lumber Company left Louisiana, my father was working with them in Mississippi.

17
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And my mother was still in Louisiana.

18
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:40,000
So I grew up in a place called De Ridder, Louisiana, between Lake Charles and Shreveport in Southwest Louisiana.

19
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:51,000
I went to a hot-finished board, God-pairish high school, where the only new book I ever had was the history of the Negro.

20
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
By Carter G. Woodson.

21
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:00,000
All the other books we had had pages torn out, or marked up.

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:01,000
But...

23
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Can you describe the, I'd love to hear a description of the school itself and your teachers.

24
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Well, we were in all black school.

25
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And the school was finally a pretty nice building.

26
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:25,000
Before we had the new school, we were in churches and places.

27
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:32,000
And finally, we had a school with a principal who could do electricity and heat.

28
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:37,000
And so we got lights and rather than lamps.

29
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:41,000
This was all in the 30s and 40s.

30
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And all of our teachers were African-American.

31
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
At that time, we were Negroes.

32
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
We all were Negroes.

33
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
And they were really wonderful teachers.

34
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:04,000
And they helped us to know that we were not inferior.

35
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:17,000
And we took seriously Carter G. Woodson's history that told us about Africa and the nice things about Africa.

36
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:22,000
And of course, we had the church.

37
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:33,000
The church was very important because the ministers and the leaders insisted that we hold our heads high.

38
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:40,000
And we took learning seriously.

39
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:46,000
And whatever we did, do it with an attitude of excellence.

40
00:03:46,000 --> 00:04:00,000
And to walk and approach those who hated us with humility for humility could not be humiliated.

41
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:08,000
And we learned that and became really strong.

42
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:12,000
And I made goals and made choices.

43
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,000
I worked from the time I was seven.

44
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:21,000
I worked taking care of a little white girl for a while.

45
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
And then I worked in a beauty shop, cleaning the beauty shop.

46
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And I worked in homes, cleaning homes.

47
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
While also going to school?

48
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:36,000
While going to high school.

49
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:50,000
And met some very interesting white people who seemed to appreciate the fact that I wanted not to just do that always.

50
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:59,000
And there was one woman who came, a camp poke was in Leesville not far from us.

51
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:03,000
And that was time doing World War II.

52
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:07,000
And these soldiers were there.

53
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:09,000
And their wives came.

54
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And one woman came from Ohio.

55
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And she hired me to come and help her.

56
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:23,000
She insisted that I sit at the table and eat with her.

57
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:29,000
And I just felt, you know, but she was very nice about it.

58
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
We sat and she talked.

59
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And I was a sophomore in college.

60
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:39,000
And she gave me magazines to read.

61
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:44,000
And she would talk about what we had read.

62
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:53,000
And when she left, she said to me that I was the only person that she felt comfortable with in that place.

63
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
I wish I could remember her name.

64
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Where was she from?

65
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:00,000
From somewhere in Ohio.

66
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:11,000
And I'll tell you later how I learned why the majority of southerners didn't let us eat together.

67
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
But she insisted on not doing that.

68
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:22,000
Well, I went from there to Southern University in Scotland, Bill Louisiana.

69
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
And I finished Southern.

70
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:34,000
Well, while I was there, of course, I came in contact with very interesting leaders,

71
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Mordecai Wyatt Johnson, W.E.B. Du Bois, and all of them came and talked to us and inspired us.

72
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:59,000
And when I left there in 1944, I knew that I couldn't, well, before that in my senior year,

73
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:05,000
I went up into the state of Washington, Longview, WA.

74
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:10,000
And I worked in the shipyards in Longview, WA.

75
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
So how did you end up there doing that kind of work?

76
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
My sister had gone there.

77
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Her husband had moved there, old back in the thirties.

78
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
And she lived in Longview, WA.

79
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:34,000
And I went there to work in the shipyards to earn enough money to finish Southern.

80
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:43,000
And I had had a lot of experience in personnel working with the dean of women.

81
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,000
So I applied for a job in personnel at the shipyards and they laughed at me.

82
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:59,000
It was very highly discriminating, even there during that time of the war.

83
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
So what job did you end up doing there?

84
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:09,000
I ended up cleaning ships, working in gyro rooms and cleaning ships.

85
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And my manager, my supervisor, felt she said, this is not the kind of work for you.

86
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
And she tried, but nothing happened.

87
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:32,000
You often hear about African American women with jobs during the war that last hired first fired.

88
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:35,000
What kind of experience did you have?

89
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Well, I only wanted to be there for a while.

90
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:47,000
But the women who worked with me, both black and white, they had children.

91
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
And we were on the graveyard ship.

92
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:58,000
So I came in well rested and they would fall asleep.

93
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:02,000
And I would awake them when the supervisor was coming.

94
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
And they appreciated that.

95
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
So you were working alongside white women as well as black women?

96
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:12,000
White women and black women.

97
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,000
And how was that experience like?

98
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Well, it was a nice experience.

99
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:23,000
They knew that I was a college student.

100
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:34,000
And they felt that, you know, I shouldn't be there and should get go back as soon as I could.

101
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,000
And I did.

102
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,000
I went back and graduated at Southern.

103
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
And when I graduated with my mother's blessings, I went to LA.

104
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Let me just ask again about Washington.

105
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
Was that really your first time outside of the South?

106
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:55,000
That was my first time out of the South.

107
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:01,000
And did that do anything to you as far as seeing how things were in another part of the country?

108
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,000
Yes.

109
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:06,000
African Americans were segregated in that little town.

110
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:09,000
They all lived together.

111
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:12,000
They went to the same church.

112
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:21,000
But they could go to an integrated school.

113
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:27,000
But they lived in an segregated neighborhood.

114
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,000
But they were very much separated.

115
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:36,000
They didn't, the kids didn't interchange visits or anything like that.

116
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,000
Even there at that time.

117
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,000
Did that surprise you or did it seem expected?

118
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,000
Do you think at that time for you?

119
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:48,000
No, I just expected that.

120
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:55,000
You know, I didn't know what the difference should have.

121
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
Well, I felt that it should have been different.

122
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:10,000
But especially working, I thought that I would be able to work, do something different than cleaning ships.

123
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:22,000
But I was very lucky that they were finished and didn't have all of that stuff that caused long problems.

124
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Yes.

125
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:33,000
I was very lucky because what we did, we prepared the ships for sailing.

126
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:37,000
You know, the first voyage trip.

127
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:39,000
We prepared them for that.

128
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:43,000
And of course, we never went on a voyage.

129
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:44,000
Right.

130
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
Very interesting.

131
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:54,000
I saw the ocean for the first time.

132
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:03,000
We went to the Pacific Ocean and I was, oh, I thought this must be all the water in the world.

133
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,000
And it was such a nice experience.

134
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Portland, Oregon was a very beautiful city.

135
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Lots of roses.

136
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:21,000
And my brother-in-law would take me to places to so that we could see Mount,

137
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:31,000
or that Mount didn't just have the terrible Mount St. Helens was in our back.

138
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:34,000
We could see it from our back door.

139
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:37,000
And it had snow then.

140
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:41,000
Snow on Mount St. Helen all year round.

141
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,000
It looks different now.

142
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:49,000
I bet after that volcanic action, yes.

143
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,000
So, okay.

144
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Work with the machines a little bit.

145
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:01,000
So, you graduated and you were saying and then decided to move to us hands.

146
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:02,000
Yes.

147
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:10,000
I applied for, well, after having worked in Washington, I knew that I did not have to work

148
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:17,000
for the amount of money that they were paying in Louisiana for teachers.

149
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:26,000
And that was the only, I could have gone to work at Camp Polk (later Fort Polk), Louisiana as in the laundry or something like that.

150
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:33,000
But those were the only jobs for college graduates in Louisiana at that time.

151
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:40,000
And you either teacher or maintenance person.

152
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,000
So, I applied for a job in Shreveport.

153
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:56,000
They wanted me to teach high school English and do the library for $50 a month.

154
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:59,000
And I thought, no.

155
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
And I decided that.

156
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:07,000
And my mother, my mother was a very smart woman.

157
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:11,000
And she said,

158
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:17,000
when you go to college,

159
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:22,000
they wash you down and you change.

160
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:28,000
And you don't fit

161
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:31,000
in the place.

162
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:35,000
And I didn't understand what she was saying.

163
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:39,000
I didn't understand what she was saying.

164
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:46,000
But she knew that

165
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:55,000
at that time they taught us in these places very differently.

166
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:02,000
And we felt that

167
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:07,000
we spoke correct English.

168
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:13,000
And we didn't use the dialect.

169
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Were there others in your family who had gone to college?

170
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,000
Not at that time.

171
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:21,000
I was the youngest and the first.

172
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:24,000
How many siblings do you have?

173
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,000
Seven of us.

174
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:31,000
I had five sisters and one brother.

175
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:34,000
All of that.

176
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:41,000
But she gave me her blessing.

177
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:48,000
And I was very happy that I wanted to achieve.

178
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:55,000
And now when I am a mother and as old as I am,

179
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:01,000
I understand what she was saying.

180
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:06,000
And how that can make a difference

181
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:10,000
with your parents, especially.

182
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:14,000
She had wanted me to follow in her footsteps

183
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:19,000
being a midwife and a healer.

184
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:21,000
And I didn't want that.

185
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:24,000
So it's a bit bittersweet?

186
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:30,000
Yes. She wanted to teach me her methods.

187
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:39,000
She had a cure for pneumonia before penicillin.

188
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:41,000
And it was penicillin.

189
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:43,000
But we didn't know that.

190
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:46,000
It was definitely penicillin.

191
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:53,000
When we would put the pigs on a floor, feed them grain,

192
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:59,000
pure mesh that would get in their hooves and mold.

193
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:07,000
She would boil that, boil them, and give them the doctor would say

194
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:12,000
to people who had, I can't help you, go see Mary.

195
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,000
And she would cure them with that tea.

196
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:23,000
She also used oyster shells, red hot oyster shells and water

197
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:28,000
cool that for kidney problems.

198
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And they know now that oyster shells have a special medicine

199
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
that they use now to cure kidney infections.

200
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:48,000
She was very, a very smart woman with very little formal education.

201
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,000
How had she learned her art?

202
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:52,000
I don't know.

203
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:57,000
I really don't know how she had learned that.

204
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:03,000
But her mother, she had a sister who was 10 years old

205
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:06,000
at the end of slavery.

206
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:11,000
And she was born in 18, in 1890, something new.

207
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:20,000
So she probably knew how to go and find the herbs and plants.

208
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,000
And she could do that.

209
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:28,000
She could go and find plants and knew these plants that could serve

210
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:35,000
as a cure for certain things, and especially for women problems.

211
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:40,000
Just fascinating.

212
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:44,000
And so your family saw you off to Los Angeles?

213
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:46,000
Los Angeles.

214
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Yes.

215
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:50,000
And I went to Los Angeles.

216
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
I knew I went with a high school classmate who had a brother

217
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:59,000
who was living in Skid Row.

218
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:05,000
And we went and stayed in a hotel on Fifth Street,

219
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:10,000
very iffy place in Los Angeles at that time.

220
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:15,000
But a lot of people were transits were there.

221
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:19,000
And I went and stayed there a few days.

222
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And then I met a woman on the bus.

223
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
And I told her I had come, just come to town.

224
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:34,000
And I thought there would be a YWCA for black women.

225
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:38,000
There was not a YWCA there.

226
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:41,000
And I didn't know what to do.

227
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:46,000
So she said, well, give me a phone number.

228
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:48,000
No, we were in Los Angeles.

229
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:49,000
Yeah.

230
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:51,000
And if I could just ask you, I forgot to say,

231
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:53,000
ask you what year that was when you first went.

232
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,000
That was in 1944 when I went to Los Angeles.

233
00:19:58,000 --> 00:19:59,000
Great.

234
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:02,000
And you were just saying you met a woman on the bus?

235
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:03,000
Yes.

236
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:05,000
And what happened?

237
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,000
I was sitting in the back.

238
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:09,000
And I saw this woman.

239
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:13,000
And she looked very intelligent and very friendly.

240
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:21,000
I had been taught that we could trust certain people.

241
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
And you can tell who you can trust.

242
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:33,000
And I went, I got up and went and sat beside her.

243
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:37,000
And she introduced herself and told me a joke.

244
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:39,000
When I told her I had just come.

245
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
She said, oh, these people are coming in.

246
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
Coming into town, she said.

247
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:50,000
And one day a lady was on the bus.

248
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And she sat beside a person.

249
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:57,000
And this woman was just coming from the south.

250
00:20:57,000 --> 00:20:59,000
She was eating on the bus.

251
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:02,000
And the lady said, we don't eat on the bus.

252
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:06,000
And she asked the woman, how long you been here?

253
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
And the woman told us she had been there for many years.

254
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:12,000
She said, well, when I've been here long as you,

255
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:16,000
I won't eat on the bus either.

256
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,000
And we had a good laugh.

257
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:23,000
And I told her my problem that I was on Skid Row

258
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:25,000
and I didn't want to be there.

259
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:29,000
And she gave me a phone that said, call me if you decide

260
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:31,000
that it's not where you want to be.

261
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:34,000
And when I called her, she said,

262
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:37,000
I could come and live with her.

263
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And she had been there for many years

264
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:44,000
and was well known in the community.

265
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:48,000
And she introduced me to all of these nice people

266
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
to my sororities sisters.

267
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:54,000
And so I was well on the way.

268
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:00,000
And her name was Mozelle Moore.

269
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:01,000
Very interesting.

270
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And did you start looking for work then as well?

271
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,000
I found work right away.

272
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:14,000
And I worked and well, I applied for teaching job.

273
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:19,000
And of course, there were no black teachers in Los Angeles

274
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:21,000
at that time.

275
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:25,000
There was one black high school teacher.

276
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:31,000
And I was told that I would have to have a California credential,

277
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:32,000
of course.

278
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:37,000
So I went back to California State University, Los Angeles, got a credential.

279
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:40,000
And then I was hired as a teacher.

280
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:45,000
But first before that, I was hired as a clerk

281
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:50,000
with the Los Angeles City Schools

282
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:56,000
as a, in a classified section.

283
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:59,000
And that, the classified section included people

284
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:03,000
who didn't have certificates.

285
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:07,000
There were janitors and clerks.

286
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,000
And so I worked as a clerk in a place

287
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:15,000
where they gave the tests for classified employees.

288
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:17,000
And that was very interesting.

289
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:18,000
And went back to school.

290
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:22,000
Well, I met my husband and we got married.

291
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:26,000
And I went back to school and got my credential.

292
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:30,000
And then I started teaching in elementary school.

293
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
So can you tell me, I want to ask about your teaching,

294
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:35,000
but can you tell me about meeting your husband?

295
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:38,000
Yes.

296
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:45,000
I, one of my sorority sisters took me to a Methodist church.

297
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:52,000
And I remember one evening we were having a meeting

298
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:55,000
with young people.

299
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:58,000
And he walked in and I said to her,

300
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:02,000
he was such an intelligent, looking man.

301
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:05,000
I said, who is that man?

302
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:11,000
And she said, oh girl, he has lots of girl friends.

303
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:14,000
You don't want to get involved with him.

304
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:21,000
But we spoke and I found out that he had also graduated from seven.

305
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:27,000
And I met, you know, we met.

306
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:33,000
And he became sort of interested.

307
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:38,000
But it was not a love at first sight.

308
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,000
No, it wasn't that.

309
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:42,000
Because we both were mature.

310
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,000
But we were friends.

311
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:53,000
And I remember one time I had to do a presentation at the church.

312
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,000
And I didn't have a decent dress.

313
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:01,000
And I asked him to loan me some money to get a hat and a dress.

314
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:03,000
And he loaned me the money.

315
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:08,000
And when I paid him back, he said, well, I wasn't worried

316
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:12,000
because I knew you didn't want anybody to have anything on you.

317
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,000
And he gave me the money back.

318
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:18,000
And that's the kind of person he was.

319
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:28,000
And I remember one time we had a meeting with the students from USC.

320
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:39,000
And I made the spaghetti and fixed all the food and said the blessing and the prayer.

321
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:41,000
And he was impressed.

322
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:46,000
And then we started seriously growing in love.

323
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:52,000
And we married in 1947.

324
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:57,000
And was he already involved with CORE at that time?

325
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:03,000
Yes, he was involved with CORE and had been since 1942.

326
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:12,000
And he was also involved with another organization called Drew, AM Drew.

327
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:22,000
And they were working against segregation in hotels and hotels.

328
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:24,000
Do you know what that stands for?

329
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:25,000
Drew.

330
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:27,000
That was a person's name.

331
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:30,000
It was just an organization.

332
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:33,000
It was an organization started by that name.

333
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:38,000
But he was also working with CORE at that time.

334
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:44,000
But not very, it wasn't very much going on.

335
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:54,000
But by 1960, 1958, CORE was really doing a lot.

336
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:03,000
We were doing stores asking for a fair employment.

337
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:15,000
And banks asking for fair employment at that time in our area where that was predominantly black and Los Angeles around Central Avenue.

338
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:20,000
And that is Central Los Angeles.

339
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Banks, stores, and other businesses did not hire us except as maintenance people, janitors.

340
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:44,000
So we picketed them and negotiated with them to hire young people who needed no more than a high school graduate to do what they were doing.

341
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:50,000
To become salespeople and boxboys.

342
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:59,000
And we insisted that they trained them for management.

343
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:05,000
And we were very successful with the grocery stores.

344
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:08,000
The banks were very reluctant.

345
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:13,000
But we picketed the banks and negotiated with them.

346
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:20,000
And finally, they hired tellers and started training people for management.

347
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:27,000
Who were some of CORE's allies?

348
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:32,000
I'm sort of interested in what kinds of people worked with you and who CORE worked with.

349
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:37,000
We were intergratial.

350
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:58,000
When we went into, well, in 1959, Jesse M. Unruh, who was a representative, passed the bill making accommodations in segregated accommodations illegal.

351
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:05,000
So we had both blacks and whites in CORE.

352
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:19,000
And the ACLU, you know, we were friends with people in the ACLU and lawyers and that type of people.

353
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:35,000
We would go out in our car with suitcases and the children and go to motels and hotels and ask for a room and be denied.

354
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:40,000
And then the white couple would come after us and get a room.

355
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,000
And so we sued those people.

356
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:46,000
We would bring suit against them.

357
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:58,000
And there was a young lawyer who did cases for us pro bono.

358
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:01,000
And we had success in suing them.

359
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:05,000
And they would finally change.

360
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:13,000
Of course, I believe that any law that comes about isn't worth much until it has been tested.

361
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:19,000
So we set out to test that law and we're successful in breaking down.

362
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:28,000
I think we did it more quickly than it would have happened if we had not done the test.

363
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:32,000
Can I ask you what drove you up, Moadabid?

364
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:46,000
Well, I guess I had always been taught to resist, but we couldn't act overtly.

365
00:30:46,000 --> 00:31:01,000
And we did that with just acting ombley and standing tall and facing these people without being subservient.

366
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:07,000
And that was instilled in us.

367
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:15,000
And so when I had the opportunity to act openly, came natural.

368
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:24,000
Just came natural to do this because I knew it was wrong.

369
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And I made that we were treated.

370
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And when I could do something to prevent it, it was just a normal thing to do.

371
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:47,000
So jumping around just a little bit, when you started teaching, what year was that that you had your first actual teaching job?

372
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:49,000
In 1955.

373
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:52,000
And at that point, how many African Americans were teaching?

374
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:54,000
Well, quite a few.

375
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:56,000
Yes, there were quite a few things.

376
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:57,000
So things had changed?

377
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:01,000
Things had changed the lot when I started teaching.

378
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:09,000
Most of the teachers at my school were African Americans, young, very young teachers.

379
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:20,000
And all of the children were African Americans, maybe one or two who were not.

380
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:26,000
I can remember one time, a little boy, a white boy was there.

381
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:31,000
And he got into trouble somehow.

382
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:35,000
And he was in the vice principal's office.

383
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:41,000
And the vice principal said to him, you don't have to be here.

384
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:46,000
I will send you to any school you want to go.

385
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:48,000
You don't have to be here.

386
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:53,000
He didn't know I was outside listening.

387
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:57,000
And this kid, he left.

388
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:01,000
He left, I don't know where he went.

389
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,000
But those are the kinds of things that you heard.

390
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
What was your reaction to that when you heard that?

391
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:15,000
Well, I just felt that I didn't say anything to him because he had one time told me.

392
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:25,000
That if I didn't like it here, I should go to another country because I was very active.

393
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:35,000
And I would put up black people on the wall for the children.

394
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:44,000
Between Abraham Lincoln and George Washington on Presidents Day, I would put Frederick Douglass, with all his beers.

395
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:48,000
Tell the children about that.

396
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:53,000
And I was active.

397
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:56,000
I was demonstrating then.

398
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,000
And they knew that.

399
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:05,000
And of course I was wearing my hair natural.

400
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:13,000
Nobody else was except, I guess, the singer.

401
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:16,000
Abbey Lincoln, the actress.

402
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:19,000
And what was her name?

403
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:22,000
That singer who did folk songs.

404
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:24,000
It'll come to me.

405
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:29,000
But we were the only three people that I knew who were doing this.

406
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:36,000
And it was very disturbing to people for us to begin to do that.

407
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:40,000
What did that symbolize for you?

408
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:43,000
Well, I had bets.

409
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:48,000
For the first time, I met people who had come from Africa.

410
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:50,000
And we were friends.

411
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,000
And this woman was so beautiful.

412
00:34:53,000 --> 00:35:02,000
And she had her hair short and not pressed just what we call nappy hair.

413
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:07,000
And I thought how beautiful that was.

414
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:13,000
And I decided I would cut my hair and wear it like that.

415
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:17,000
And people wondered why I wanted to do that.

416
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:20,000
They thought, I don't know.

417
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:24,000
But that's something.

418
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:26,000
But I did it.

419
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:29,000
And my husband was proud.

420
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:32,000
And sometimes I would go back and straighten it.

421
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:37,000
And he would say, well, people do it.

422
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:40,000
You know, you can make, he said, but that's not your hair.

423
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:42,000
Like that.

424
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:55,000
And I took his word for it and had done it this way since 1950s.

425
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:57,000
Wow.

426
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:00,000
So you were putting up, I just love the image,

427
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:05,000
you're putting up Frederick Douglass on the wall.

428
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And with George Washington, he really went on Lincoln.

429
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:11,000
And clearly, trying to teach,

430
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:14,000
puts in black role models up for the students.

431
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:15,000
Right.

432
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:16,000
And I did that.

433
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:23,000
And I would put out brown paint color for the children to paint themselves.

434
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:26,000
And that was not popular.

435
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:33,000
Because they didn't want to think of themselves as black and beautiful.

436
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:41,000
But one of the most precious moments for me was one time a little girl came

437
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:46,000
while I was teaching and said to me, she was crying.

438
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:50,000
Teacher called me black.

439
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:53,000
And I looked at I said, but you are.

440
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:57,000
You are black and you are beautiful.

441
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:06,000
And a few times, a few days later, somebody called him black and I heard her say,

442
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:07,000
yes, I am.

443
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:11,000
And I'm beautiful because teacher told me so.

444
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:14,000
And that was a precious moment.

445
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:16,000
Precious.

446
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:22,000
She said it just like, I'm beautiful because teacher told me so.

447
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:27,000
And sometimes they would come in and I would walk in and knew they would say,

448
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,000
look at teacher's hair.

449
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:31,000
Look at teacher's hair.

450
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:33,000
You know, punching one another.

451
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:36,000
Looks just like mine.

452
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:38,000
You know?

453
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:42,000
Made a difference with them.

454
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:49,000
So can you tell us a little bit about how that led to your writing?

455
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:51,000
Oh, yes.

456
00:37:51,000 --> 00:38:00,000
At that time, there were very few books that showed us in a positive image.

457
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:08,000
We had pictures of eating watermelon and red lips and all of that, you know, rings and the nose.

458
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:16,000
And now Du Bois and Langston Hughes had done some books for children.

459
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:19,000
But there weren't many.

460
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:27,000
And I knew a publisher in Los Angeles who did my book, Lillie of Watts.

461
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:36,000
And I asked him to publish some books for my children, you know, and he said, write them.

462
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:39,000
If you write them, I'll publish them.

463
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:43,000
And I said, no, I am not a writer.

464
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:48,000
And I insisted and I wrote that book and he published it.

465
00:38:48,000 --> 00:39:00,000
And it was reviewed by outstanding reviewers and kind of heady stuff", to be a writer.

466
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:10,000
But I soon learned after a couple of times that it wasn't that easy.

467
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:14,400
And I've got a lot of rejection slips.

468
00:39:14,400 --> 00:39:23,940
And then one day I met a young man at Scholastic who had just graduated from Harvard.

469
00:39:23,940 --> 00:39:34,280
He was working there and I had gone in to see a black editor at another place.

470
00:39:34,280 --> 00:39:37,560
And she sent me to see him.

471
00:39:37,560 --> 00:39:48,360
And I went to see him and he took me, that the Harvard had just opened up its restaurant.

472
00:39:48,360 --> 00:39:52,040
It's a place for women to go and eat.

473
00:39:52,040 --> 00:39:57,400
And he took me to go there and that was very nice.

474
00:39:57,400 --> 00:40:04,320
And I told him about a book I wanted to write.

475
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:10,520
And he said, right, and I wrote a book called The Liquid Trap.

476
00:40:10,520 --> 00:40:16,560
And they thought maybe this was about alcohol.

477
00:40:16,560 --> 00:40:23,640
But it was about these sinkholes in Louisiana, sand traps.

478
00:40:23,640 --> 00:40:28,800
You know, you get caught in the sand.

479
00:40:28,800 --> 00:40:35,840
And I did that book.

480
00:40:35,840 --> 00:40:44,000
And he published it and gave it to, showed it to another editor there.

481
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:50,880
And she introduced me to a young editor, Barbara Lalicki.

482
00:40:50,880 --> 00:41:00,640
And Barbara was young enough to take a risk with an African American writer.

483
00:41:00,640 --> 00:41:03,400
So she asked me to write a book.

484
00:41:03,400 --> 00:41:07,600
And I wrote Ty's One-Man Band for her.

485
00:41:07,600 --> 00:41:12,280
And that was the very first book on reading Rainbow.

486
00:41:12,280 --> 00:41:13,280
Ty's One-Man Band.

487
00:41:13,280 --> 00:41:14,280
Oh, it was.

488
00:41:14,280 --> 00:41:16,760
Wonderful.

489
00:41:16,760 --> 00:41:23,640
And I stayed with her and wrote most of these books with Barbara.

490
00:41:23,640 --> 00:41:26,840
Were there many African Americans in publishing?

491
00:41:26,840 --> 00:41:27,840
Not editors.

492
00:41:27,840 --> 00:41:28,840
Not publishers, right?

493
00:41:28,840 --> 00:41:30,360
Not publishing, no.

494
00:41:30,360 --> 00:41:34,160
And I think that is the problem.

495
00:41:34,160 --> 00:41:45,480
There are no editors who look at our work and can see and appreciate where we're coming

496
00:41:45,480 --> 00:41:46,480
from.

497
00:41:46,480 --> 00:41:50,800
There are some, of course, there are white editors who do.

498
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:57,080
But there are no black editors in these major publishing houses.

499
00:41:57,080 --> 00:41:59,720
Not many, not many, not many.

500
00:41:59,720 --> 00:42:07,960
And of course, now we have less than maybe 1% of all the books that are published, written

501
00:42:07,960 --> 00:42:12,840
by, by and for black children.

502
00:42:12,840 --> 00:42:14,840
Maybe less than 1%.

503
00:42:14,840 --> 00:42:18,840
All children's books.

504
00:42:18,840 --> 00:42:19,840
Yeah.

505
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:26,400
But you were able to connect with some people that understood this.

506
00:42:26,400 --> 00:42:27,400
Oh, yes.

507
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:43,880
Barbara appreciated what I was doing and had, my first book was a book, not my first, but

508
00:42:43,880 --> 00:42:53,200
my mom needs me was a book about a little boy who, some other had a new baby.

509
00:42:53,200 --> 00:42:57,600
And he was very worried that she didn't love him anymore.

510
00:42:57,600 --> 00:42:59,440
And he went through that.

511
00:42:59,440 --> 00:43:01,720
She went through that with him.

512
00:43:01,720 --> 00:43:06,280
And he would go out and people would want him to do things away from home.

513
00:43:06,280 --> 00:43:07,680
And he said, I can't.

514
00:43:07,680 --> 00:43:08,680
My mom needs me.

515
00:43:08,680 --> 00:43:10,080
He has to get back.

516
00:43:10,080 --> 00:43:12,680
I grew up with my grandchildren.

517
00:43:12,680 --> 00:43:13,680
Oh, really?

518
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:19,680
Let me see if I can find him.

519
00:43:19,680 --> 00:43:23,800
Yes, yes, yes.

520
00:43:23,800 --> 00:43:29,520
This book was the one.

521
00:43:29,520 --> 00:43:37,120
At first, the illustrator made the character's white.

522
00:43:37,120 --> 00:43:42,440
And my editor showed it to me and I said, no way.

523
00:43:42,440 --> 00:43:44,640
No way.

524
00:43:44,640 --> 00:43:53,040
I could not do that because my purpose was to have our children see themselves.

525
00:43:53,040 --> 00:43:57,200
And I'm sure that's what most black writers wanted.

526
00:43:57,200 --> 00:44:01,320
For the children to see themselves and their families.

527
00:44:01,320 --> 00:44:10,880
And not only for black children, but for all children to see us as we are, you know?

528
00:44:10,880 --> 00:44:24,120
And to know who we are and see us as, now there was one book early that a snowy day by

529
00:44:24,120 --> 00:44:25,960
Jack Keats.

530
00:44:25,960 --> 00:44:27,960
My daughter's favorite book.

531
00:44:27,960 --> 00:44:32,960
See, and that was very nice.

532
00:44:32,960 --> 00:44:43,520
One of the first, he did that to show these children as normal and healthy and really

533
00:44:43,520 --> 00:44:47,000
children.

534
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:58,920
And all of my books though have a choice, courage and change.

535
00:44:58,920 --> 00:45:05,560
Every character has to make choices and then they have to stand by the choices.

536
00:45:05,560 --> 00:45:07,360
It's a good one.

537
00:45:07,360 --> 00:45:09,720
And if they do, they will grow.

538
00:45:09,720 --> 00:45:11,800
They will change.

539
00:45:11,800 --> 00:45:17,520
And everyone has to do that even here.

540
00:45:17,520 --> 00:45:19,520
My mama needs me.

541
00:45:19,520 --> 00:45:20,520
Right.

542
00:45:20,520 --> 00:45:21,520
Yes.

543
00:45:21,520 --> 00:45:22,520
Yes.

544
00:45:22,520 --> 00:45:26,880
When you were still teaching, did you ever sort of field test the books with the kids that

545
00:45:26,880 --> 00:45:30,080
you were teaching and bringing your stories to them?

546
00:45:30,080 --> 00:45:31,080
No.

547
00:45:31,080 --> 00:45:34,600
I went around the country with the books.

548
00:45:34,600 --> 00:45:36,720
I wasn't teaching then.

549
00:45:36,720 --> 00:45:37,720
Okay.

550
00:45:37,720 --> 00:45:41,360
I was writing and consulting.

551
00:45:41,360 --> 00:45:50,680
But I would go to schools across the nation and talk to children and read my books and

552
00:45:50,680 --> 00:46:00,200
got wonderful letters from children thanking me and telling me how much they enjoyed knowing

553
00:46:00,200 --> 00:46:04,240
the characters.

554
00:46:04,240 --> 00:46:12,000
So that was quite a pleasant experience to do the books.

555
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:17,480
And we won some interesting prizes.

556
00:46:17,480 --> 00:46:24,320
Coretta Scott King award for Justin and the Best Biscuits in the World.

557
00:46:24,320 --> 00:46:25,320
And...

558
00:46:25,320 --> 00:46:27,320
You know what's going on?

559
00:46:27,320 --> 00:46:31,080
You might as well play a chord for this work, but I'll have to do it.

560
00:46:31,080 --> 00:46:39,320
This one won the Coretta Scott King award for the Best Book.

561
00:46:39,320 --> 00:46:46,400
And this one won the Christopher Award, Mississippi.

562
00:46:46,400 --> 00:46:48,160
No, not this one.

563
00:46:48,160 --> 00:46:56,360
This one won the Jane Adams, Jane Addams Children's Book Award.

564
00:46:56,360 --> 00:47:06,720
And this one Coretta Scott King, Mississippi Challenge notable book and the Christopher Best

565
00:47:06,720 --> 00:47:07,720
Book award.

566
00:47:07,720 --> 00:47:14,520
They talked a little bit about that book which maybe has a little bit of a, you know,

567
00:47:14,520 --> 00:47:16,840
tardy, maybe a little bit older audience.

568
00:47:16,840 --> 00:47:18,960
Yes, this is for young adults.

569
00:47:18,960 --> 00:47:22,800
And this also is for young adults.

570
00:47:22,800 --> 00:47:32,000
This one is about the slavery doing, the Revolutionary War and Elizabeth "Mum Bett" Freeman winning her

571
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:38,680
freedom and Massachusetts through the Massachusetts Constitution.

572
00:47:38,680 --> 00:47:49,920
And this one is for young adults about the 1964 and 1968 Mississippi Challenge and all

573
00:47:50,000 --> 00:48:00,480
about Mississippi and how the people in Mississippi had struggled since the beginning of time to

574
00:48:00,480 --> 00:48:02,560
free themselves.

575
00:48:02,560 --> 00:48:13,280
And finally in 1964 they went to the Democratic National Convention in Vanilo, Hamer,

576
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:16,360
with President Johnson and all of them.

577
00:48:16,360 --> 00:48:19,480
And she had an opportunity to say to them,

578
00:48:19,480 --> 00:48:25,000
it didn't come here to just say do nothing.

579
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:28,360
We came to take our seats.

580
00:48:28,360 --> 00:48:37,920
And President Johnson promised that they would have a time and then they went back and did

581
00:48:37,920 --> 00:48:48,360
all of that legal work to make possible the seating of their delegate.

582
00:48:48,360 --> 00:48:55,360
And of course I wrote a piece about that for The Big Book for Peace, which said there

583
00:48:55,360 --> 00:48:59,200
can be no peace without justice.

584
00:48:59,200 --> 00:49:10,680
And how they went to Washington and stood waiting for the Congress to decide whether they

585
00:49:10,680 --> 00:49:14,520
would seat them or the white delegation.

586
00:49:14,520 --> 00:49:19,240
They lost that, but they won.

587
00:49:19,240 --> 00:49:20,240
They won.

588
00:49:20,240 --> 00:49:29,240
And it's vital the fact that they were not seated and then they came back and did the work

589
00:49:29,240 --> 00:49:36,320
that made it possible for the Voting Rights Act 1965 to be passed.

590
00:49:36,320 --> 00:49:50,520
And we're really concerned today that the right to vote is in danger here in the 21st

591
00:49:50,520 --> 00:49:51,520
century.

592
00:49:51,520 --> 00:49:57,400
What kind of work do you hope that your writing does?

593
00:49:57,400 --> 00:50:08,680
Well, I hope that it tells children, black and white, all children that they can make

594
00:50:08,680 --> 00:50:11,480
a difference.

595
00:50:11,480 --> 00:50:20,760
And all of my books point that out that you do what you feel is right.

596
00:50:20,760 --> 00:50:34,000
For instance, this book, Alex Premma, this young boy was forced to read by a white girl

597
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:37,000
in Virginia.

598
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:40,600
And she told him he could go up to Connecticut.

599
00:50:40,600 --> 00:50:44,280
I think it was Connecticut.

600
00:50:44,280 --> 00:50:47,400
And he would be free.

601
00:50:47,400 --> 00:50:55,600
But he knew better and his mother told him that he must not read because he was a slave.

602
00:50:55,600 --> 00:51:00,120
And he could be sold into away from her.

603
00:51:00,120 --> 00:51:04,800
But she insisted and this girl made him read.

604
00:51:04,800 --> 00:51:08,800
And one day he got very interested in reading.

605
00:51:08,800 --> 00:51:12,920
And one day the grandmother caught him reading.

606
00:51:12,920 --> 00:51:15,400
And she tried to take the book away from him.

607
00:51:15,400 --> 00:51:17,360
It was a Premma.

608
00:51:17,360 --> 00:51:19,440
He wouldn't give it up.

609
00:51:19,440 --> 00:51:23,400
And she hit him in the face with her writing crust.

610
00:51:23,400 --> 00:51:26,760
He still wouldn't give it up.

611
00:51:26,760 --> 00:51:36,480
And his children had that Premma in Connecticut.

612
00:51:36,480 --> 00:51:45,920
So these are the kinds of things that I try to show children, not tell them, but show

613
00:51:45,920 --> 00:51:51,200
them that you make choices.

614
00:51:51,200 --> 00:51:58,480
And you must, if it is a good choice, and a good choice is what is good for all living

615
00:51:58,480 --> 00:52:03,280
things, not just for you, but for all living things.

616
00:52:03,280 --> 00:52:06,240
When you know that is a good choice, then you have

617
00:52:06,240 --> 00:52:08,360
courage.

618
00:52:08,360 --> 00:52:14,560
And courage will help you to stick with that thing.

619
00:52:14,560 --> 00:52:15,920
And you will change.

620
00:52:15,920 --> 00:52:17,640
You will grow.

621
00:52:17,640 --> 00:52:21,200
And all of my characters show that.

622
00:52:21,200 --> 00:52:29,880
And I believe that wholeheartedly, that courage will give us that kind of stick to it in

623
00:52:29,880 --> 00:52:34,000
this, to let us do what is right.

624
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:42,680
And that is why I was able to do the kinds of things that I did like Nazis"

625
00:52:42,680 --> 00:52:47,480
and go to jail, take that risk.

626
00:52:47,480 --> 00:52:51,240
Because that's what making the choice is.

627
00:52:51,240 --> 00:52:52,400
Choosing is a risk.

628
00:52:52,400 --> 00:52:55,400
I don't want to sound preaching.

629
00:52:55,400 --> 00:52:56,400
No, not at all.

630
00:52:56,400 --> 00:52:57,400
No, not at all.

631
00:52:57,400 --> 00:53:01,880
But it is.

632
00:53:01,880 --> 00:53:04,280
That's what choosing is.

633
00:53:04,280 --> 00:53:06,120
It's taking risks.

634
00:53:06,120 --> 00:53:15,040
And when you risk, if you have the courage, because courage is that kind of thing that comes

635
00:53:15,040 --> 00:53:22,920
from being able to listen, listen to your heart.

636
00:53:22,920 --> 00:53:25,960
And not that romantic thing.

637
00:53:25,960 --> 00:53:33,600
That inner spirit that guides you to do what is right.

638
00:53:33,600 --> 00:53:41,880
And you will learn how to go forward or step back at the right moment.

639
00:53:41,880 --> 00:53:46,240
And when you learn that, then you can grow.

640
00:53:46,240 --> 00:53:47,240
You will grow.

641
00:53:47,240 --> 00:53:49,160
You will change.

642
00:53:49,160 --> 00:53:56,080
And as millions of youths say, you won't have status.

643
00:53:56,080 --> 00:54:05,080
You will have status.

644
00:54:05,080 --> 00:54:12,880
So we've talked about your childhood and your work in Los Angeles and with core and teaching

645
00:54:12,880 --> 00:54:15,400
in the books.

646
00:54:15,400 --> 00:54:17,600
How do you see all these things connected?

647
00:54:17,600 --> 00:54:28,880
But I did book reviews for the Los Angeles Times when Johnson made available for them to

648
00:54:28,880 --> 00:54:35,360
bring out more material for multicultural understanding.

649
00:54:35,360 --> 00:54:44,800
And so I read all of those old books that came back from Du Bois and from them.

650
00:54:44,800 --> 00:54:54,560
And I was able to do names there in the camp.

651
00:54:54,560 --> 00:54:58,200
The guy who was in prison in South Africa.

652
00:54:58,200 --> 00:54:59,200
Mandela.

653
00:54:59,200 --> 00:55:03,080
Mandela's book.

654
00:55:03,080 --> 00:55:06,240
I Shall Not Be Moved.

655
00:55:06,240 --> 00:55:15,640
And I reviewed that book for the Los Angeles Times and all of Du Bois' books and James

656
00:55:15,640 --> 00:55:17,560
Baldwin's book.

657
00:55:17,560 --> 00:55:21,960
Well, I didn't review James Baldwin's book.

658
00:55:21,960 --> 00:55:26,520
James Baldwin came to speak for us at core.

659
00:55:26,520 --> 00:55:35,520
He had just written that book that was old.

660
00:55:35,520 --> 00:55:37,560
Go tell it on the map.

661
00:55:37,560 --> 00:55:38,920
No, not that one.

662
00:55:38,920 --> 00:55:48,000
It was the one that talked about Malcolm X and I know the book.

663
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:52,400
But anyway, he had just written that book.

664
00:55:52,400 --> 00:56:03,000
And the editor at Los Angeles reviewed it and I rebutted his for core.

665
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:06,040
And I rebutted his review.

666
00:56:06,040 --> 00:56:14,840
And he had said that Baldwin was a bigot in writing this book.

667
00:56:14,840 --> 00:56:28,320
And anyway, I proved from Baldwin's words that he was not because I disagree with some

668
00:56:28,320 --> 00:56:30,280
things with Baldwin.

669
00:56:30,280 --> 00:56:39,560
But I knew he was not a bit because at the end of his book he said, if we, the few that

670
00:56:39,560 --> 00:56:46,160
we are, can bring about, at least we can save this nation.

671
00:56:46,160 --> 00:56:51,320
We can work to save this nation and give it justice.

672
00:56:51,320 --> 00:56:59,480
And after I did that rebuttal, he printed it and he asked me to review books.

673
00:56:59,480 --> 00:57:01,480
Oh, yeah.

674
00:57:01,480 --> 00:57:02,480
Great.

675
00:57:02,480 --> 00:57:06,000
And reviewing books, I decided that's not for me.

676
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:09,240
I need to write books.

677
00:57:09,240 --> 00:57:13,240
And I just talk about the criticize of the people's work.

678
00:57:13,240 --> 00:57:19,160
Let me try to do something too.

679
00:57:19,160 --> 00:57:31,800
So, but I will tell you some exciting moments in my life that I feel.

680
00:57:31,800 --> 00:57:33,800
Okay.

681
00:57:33,800 --> 00:57:40,040
I marched in housing tracks in Los Angeles.

682
00:57:40,040 --> 00:57:47,760
And we, they were building houses in areas near where a lot of black people lived and

683
00:57:47,760 --> 00:57:50,760
they wouldn't sell them to us.

684
00:57:50,760 --> 00:57:53,880
They wouldn't sell us those houses.

685
00:57:53,880 --> 00:57:58,160
So we pick it that, pick it them.

686
00:57:58,160 --> 00:58:11,760
And I can remember one Saturday we were picketing at a place in what is now Carson, California.

687
00:58:11,760 --> 00:58:14,160
And everything was going well.

688
00:58:14,160 --> 00:58:22,520
We had a big line, a good line and there was a Jewish person, Herbert, who had been in

689
00:58:22,520 --> 00:58:25,760
the concentration camp in Germany.

690
00:58:25,760 --> 00:58:28,800
And he was marching with us.

691
00:58:28,800 --> 00:58:30,960
He had been very active in court.

692
00:58:30,960 --> 00:58:34,640
He went on the freedom rise.

693
00:58:34,640 --> 00:58:45,960
And oh, soon the police came and they came and stood across the street watching us.

694
00:58:45,960 --> 00:58:50,280
And of course, they always brought tension.

695
00:58:50,280 --> 00:58:55,520
But after a while, the tension eased with the police.

696
00:58:55,520 --> 00:59:05,400
And then about four cars drove up full of white men dressed like noxies.

697
00:59:05,400 --> 00:59:10,920
They had on noxie uniform, including the swastika.

698
00:59:10,920 --> 00:59:19,440
And they had on their signs, their sticks were so big that they could have damaged us

699
00:59:19,440 --> 00:59:23,200
with their placards.

700
00:59:23,200 --> 00:59:30,000
And their placards read, ovens too good for Niggas.

701
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:38,440
Niggas go back to the trees, your monkeys go back to the trees.

702
00:59:38,440 --> 00:59:45,520
And I saw her, but and I was so I got worried about him.

703
00:59:45,520 --> 00:59:55,160
And I wondered if these people would make us lose our stance and become violent.

704
00:59:55,160 --> 00:59:56,840
But we had been trained.

705
00:59:56,840 --> 01:00:06,840
And finally I saw her, but leave the line in a staggering way.

706
01:00:06,840 --> 01:00:15,440
And I wondered, you know, I was very outraged.

707
01:00:15,440 --> 01:00:24,560
And I wondered if I shouldn't leave too, but I stayed and I was questioning myself,

708
01:00:24,560 --> 01:00:25,880
why am I here?

709
01:00:25,880 --> 01:00:28,640
Why am I doing this?

710
01:00:28,640 --> 01:00:38,600
Why do I want people thinking that I want to live beside white people?

711
01:00:38,600 --> 01:00:42,000
Why am I here?

712
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:47,000
And I, somebody started singing, old freedom.

713
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:50,720
This lone voice, Oh, Freedom".

714
01:00:50,720 --> 01:00:59,840
And before I be a slave, I'll be bearing in my brain and go home to my Lord and be free.

715
01:00:59,840 --> 01:01:12,960
And I thought, well, I'm not here because I want to live beside white people.

716
01:01:12,960 --> 01:01:23,520
I'm here because I want us to be able to decide where it is we want to live and we can

717
01:01:23,520 --> 01:01:28,240
have the freedom to do that.

718
01:01:28,240 --> 01:01:39,560
And I lost my anger and I felt pleased with myself that I had stayed.

719
01:01:39,560 --> 01:01:53,680
And I was there with not self-ocertiveness, but there and was at peace and was there

720
01:01:53,680 --> 01:02:01,080
a long time after the Noxys had gone home.

721
01:02:01,080 --> 01:02:10,600
And another time I had been asked to go with a group of artists and writers and sculptors

722
01:02:10,600 --> 01:02:21,720
to Nigeria, to the African Festival of Culture, where all people from the diaspora were

723
01:02:21,720 --> 01:02:23,600
coming.

724
01:02:23,600 --> 01:02:31,420
And I was the only children's book writer, so I was able to make a presentation and they

725
01:02:31,420 --> 01:02:38,640
were quite pleased that I had come because they felt that they needed more children's

726
01:02:38,640 --> 01:02:42,920
books on the continent.

727
01:02:42,920 --> 01:02:46,400
But anyway, I stayed after Nigeria.

728
01:02:46,400 --> 01:02:58,640
I went to Ghana and to other places, Cameroon and to Ghana and looked around.

729
01:02:58,640 --> 01:03:09,800
And I felt in many instances in Ghana, especially, they looked at me and they wanted to know

730
01:03:09,800 --> 01:03:12,200
who is that woman.

731
01:03:12,200 --> 01:03:19,680
She was a woman in the market where I was and somebody said she's a cacuey woman.

732
01:03:19,680 --> 01:03:20,680
She's a cacuey woman.

733
01:03:20,680 --> 01:03:25,400
They said no, I don't think she's cacuey.

734
01:03:25,400 --> 01:03:29,600
She might be a chola.

735
01:03:29,600 --> 01:03:35,480
And at that time I spoke to another lady who was not with them.

736
01:03:35,480 --> 01:03:42,160
And when they heard my voice, they said oh my god, she's a white woman.

737
01:03:42,160 --> 01:03:48,680
Oh, so you can imagine how I felt.

738
01:03:48,680 --> 01:03:51,920
And it's amazing, I don't like to think of that.

739
01:03:51,920 --> 01:04:00,880
But I can remember one time when I was a teenager, I was a freshman in college and walking

740
01:04:00,880 --> 01:04:09,560
down the street in Louisiana and soldiers were out there, were there.

741
01:04:09,560 --> 01:04:17,160
And a white soldier called to his friends and the drugstore and said hey, come see this

742
01:04:17,160 --> 01:04:21,440
pretty nigger.

743
01:04:21,440 --> 01:04:27,200
And for some reason I got that same feeling there.

744
01:04:27,200 --> 01:04:33,640
And I don't know why, but when they said oh my god, she's a white woman.

745
01:04:33,640 --> 01:04:38,520
She's not one of us.

746
01:04:38,520 --> 01:04:40,760
And that's what they were implying.

747
01:04:40,760 --> 01:04:44,520
She's not one of us.

748
01:04:44,520 --> 01:04:51,640
So I went, I knew a great poet there, Kofi Awoonor,

749
01:04:51,640 --> 01:04:58,760
And he was gracious to take me to Elmina Castle, that castle.

750
01:04:58,760 --> 01:05:07,800
And we went to that and I listened to the people, this young man talk about the people who

751
01:05:07,800 --> 01:05:10,040
had been in there.

752
01:05:10,040 --> 01:05:23,120
And he was like a person who had no, his voice was like people doing an ad on TV, no way

753
01:05:23,120 --> 01:05:25,880
of connecting.

754
01:05:25,880 --> 01:05:37,720
And at that time we walked up on the deck to see the guns and the door of no return.

755
01:05:37,720 --> 01:05:47,320
And when we walked up there and hear word these men in chains.

756
01:05:47,320 --> 01:05:51,960
And at first I thought my god, I'm hallucinating, something.

757
01:05:51,960 --> 01:05:57,000
It was a prison at that time.

758
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:00,040
It was a prison.

759
01:06:00,040 --> 01:06:08,880
But so many of us have gone there, they have understand that it's no longer so.

760
01:06:08,880 --> 01:06:17,580
So Kofi and I went and stood on the, he wanted me to see the, those big guns that were

761
01:06:17,580 --> 01:06:20,880
trained on the ships.

762
01:06:20,880 --> 01:06:28,760
So that when the slaves were about to leave, there could be no interference.

763
01:06:28,760 --> 01:06:38,800
And we went on the Atlantic Ocean and walked on the beach and I was looking up at those

764
01:06:38,800 --> 01:06:44,720
guns and listening to the sound of the ocean rolling up.

765
01:06:44,720 --> 01:06:51,200
And ocean waves always remind me of the blues for some reason.

766
01:06:51,200 --> 01:06:58,360
And I stood there and I looked up at those guns and I thought.

767
01:06:58,360 --> 01:07:07,960
I am not African and I am not American.

768
01:07:07,960 --> 01:07:14,160
We had not been allowed to carry the flag at the festival.

769
01:07:14,160 --> 01:07:20,600
And I am not protected under the flag of my country.

770
01:07:20,600 --> 01:07:23,040
And I broke down and cried.

771
01:07:23,040 --> 01:07:27,440
And Kofi said, what is it with your Americans?

772
01:07:27,440 --> 01:07:31,120
You, one of you who come here, you do that.

773
01:07:31,120 --> 01:07:34,240
And I couldn't tell him why.

774
01:07:34,240 --> 01:07:44,360
But I knew that I'm not African really and I'm not American.

775
01:07:44,360 --> 01:07:53,320
But I have a heritage of Africa and I'm born in America so I can take the best of both

776
01:07:53,320 --> 01:07:57,200
cultures and be who I am.

777
01:07:57,200 --> 01:07:59,480
And I can become whole.

778
01:07:59,480 --> 01:08:02,720
I do not.

779
01:08:02,720 --> 01:08:08,280
I am not a three fifths of a person.

780
01:08:08,280 --> 01:08:09,680
And I thought that there.

781
01:08:09,680 --> 01:08:16,480
I'm not three fifths of a person as the Constitution says on the shores of Africa.

782
01:08:16,480 --> 01:08:18,200
I felt this.

783
01:08:18,200 --> 01:08:21,600
I am not a potential.

784
01:08:21,600 --> 01:08:23,040
I am.

785
01:08:23,040 --> 01:08:27,520
And my blackness is not a lack.

786
01:08:27,520 --> 01:08:30,080
It is.

787
01:08:30,080 --> 01:08:37,400
And I felt that I am unique, unique.

788
01:08:37,400 --> 01:08:39,520
Neither one or the other.

789
01:08:39,520 --> 01:08:48,400
And I can understand why Africa does not really know us.

790
01:08:48,400 --> 01:08:50,880
It's too painful.

791
01:08:50,880 --> 01:08:53,480
We were brutally taken away.

792
01:08:53,480 --> 01:08:55,560
Never heard of again.

793
01:08:55,560 --> 01:08:57,960
Nobody ever returned.

794
01:08:57,960 --> 01:09:05,320
And the pain is so great you have to suppress that pain and forget.

795
01:09:05,320 --> 01:09:08,320
Forget.

796
01:09:08,320 --> 01:09:14,080
And now we're going back and they are beginning to see.

797
01:09:14,080 --> 01:09:17,760
We are very much a part of them.

798
01:09:17,760 --> 01:09:20,240
Very much.

799
01:09:20,240 --> 01:09:26,880
And of course I came back thinking I'm unique but when I came back I couldn't talk about

800
01:09:26,880 --> 01:09:29,160
that to anybody.

801
01:09:29,160 --> 01:09:37,760
They might think I'm being arrogant and not wanting to identify with my African heritage.

802
01:09:37,760 --> 01:09:41,360
And so I didn't say I didn't talk about it.

803
01:09:41,360 --> 01:09:49,080
But I figured not knowing and I didn't know enough about Africa.

804
01:09:49,080 --> 01:09:52,520
Three months in Africa tells you nothing.

805
01:09:52,520 --> 01:09:54,960
I didn't know enough.

806
01:09:54,960 --> 01:10:07,240
But what I could do, I could begin to find out more about my heritage and about my

807
01:10:07,240 --> 01:10:13,040
people, where they had come from.

808
01:10:13,040 --> 01:10:14,520
And I did.

809
01:10:14,520 --> 01:10:26,000
My grandmother came from Guinea and she was part of the French and ended up in Haiti.

810
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:40,120
And from Haiti after the French, the Toussaint L'Ouverture Revolution ended up in Louisiana.

811
01:10:40,120 --> 01:10:45,360
And I can find out more and become fully whole.

812
01:10:45,360 --> 01:10:48,080
And I think I've done that.

813
01:10:48,080 --> 01:10:59,880
I have looked at African religions, looked at Christian religion and philosophies and

814
01:10:59,880 --> 01:11:02,160
all of that.

815
01:11:02,160 --> 01:11:09,960
And I think I can see comparisons between Jesus and my people.

816
01:11:09,960 --> 01:11:19,160
And that is why we were able to turn the other cheek and walk the second mile.

817
01:11:19,160 --> 01:11:22,600
Yes, yes.

818
01:11:22,600 --> 01:11:34,920
And I feel that if we can finally really have a discourse about race in this country as

819
01:11:34,920 --> 01:11:42,960
the South Africans did for reconciliation, we will become healed.

820
01:11:42,960 --> 01:11:45,720
It would be a healing.

821
01:11:45,720 --> 01:11:57,240
The Kerner Commission recognized that we needed to really look at the problem of racism,

822
01:11:57,240 --> 01:12:04,160
and discuss it, but the Kerner Commission was denied.

823
01:12:04,160 --> 01:12:12,440
And we fell back into the old ways of doing things.

824
01:12:12,440 --> 01:12:20,000
And until we can make that reconciliation, we will not be healed.

825
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:22,280
What do you think it's going to take?

826
01:12:22,280 --> 01:12:26,800
It's going to take acknowledging it.

827
01:12:26,800 --> 01:12:40,240
He as the people who were oppressed and those people who are the relatives and the generations

828
01:12:40,240 --> 01:12:52,360
of the oppressors, we are going to have to sit down together and really discuss this and

829
01:12:52,360 --> 01:12:57,000
acknowledge the pain.

830
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:01,800
Because I'm sure that there is pain on both sides.

831
01:13:01,800 --> 01:13:10,240
You cannot murder, you cannot mistreat, you cannot oppress and not feel guilt.

832
01:13:10,240 --> 01:13:13,800
And guilt is very damaging.

833
01:13:13,800 --> 01:13:25,480
And you cannot be treated that way without feeling anger.

834
01:13:25,480 --> 01:13:30,880
And anger is very damaging.

835
01:13:30,880 --> 01:13:40,240
And we must come together and discuss this, this fear that they feel.

836
01:13:40,240 --> 01:13:48,320
There is so much fear of us, and we sense that.

837
01:13:48,320 --> 01:13:58,720
There's fear, there's guilt, and as anger, and there is humility and wanting and longing

838
01:13:58,720 --> 01:14:02,040
on both sides.

839
01:14:02,040 --> 01:14:13,680
I have gone to films and I have seen people who have, who are the relatives of those who

840
01:14:13,680 --> 01:14:23,200
were oppressors, mentioned that when they know their relatives, when they find out that

841
01:14:23,200 --> 01:14:30,040
their relatives were doing this, they couldn't walk out of their house for days.

842
01:14:30,040 --> 01:14:34,360
They were so depressed and they couldn't talk about it.

843
01:14:34,360 --> 01:14:43,120
You see, there's nobody who would understand, nobody who's willing to listen.

844
01:14:43,120 --> 01:14:52,280
And we are going to have to, I think, come to this reconciliation if we are to become

845
01:14:52,280 --> 01:15:02,280
a whole and not be so afraid that we have to wage wars, have soldiers everywhere.

846
01:15:02,280 --> 01:15:12,280
Right.

847
01:15:12,280 --> 01:15:22,520
That's right.

848
01:15:22,520 --> 01:15:28,440
They did it in South Africa, they did it in Australia.

849
01:15:28,440 --> 01:15:31,400
But we cannot do it.

850
01:15:31,400 --> 01:15:33,840
We tried it in Greensboro Truth and Reconciliation Commission 2004-06.

851
01:15:33,840 --> 01:15:35,880
I don't know if you followed that.

852
01:15:35,880 --> 01:15:36,880
Yeah.

853
01:15:36,880 --> 01:15:38,880
I mean, so there have been attempts.

854
01:15:38,880 --> 01:15:40,200
There have been attempts.

855
01:15:40,200 --> 01:15:42,040
And I just hope we can.

856
01:15:42,040 --> 01:15:47,960
Of course, I traveled and went to the Soviet Union on a piece mark.

857
01:15:47,960 --> 01:15:48,960
That's right.

858
01:15:48,960 --> 01:15:49,960
Yeah.

859
01:15:49,960 --> 01:15:50,960
What was that?

860
01:15:50,960 --> 01:15:55,000
Well, we were there.

861
01:15:55,000 --> 01:16:03,680
Every town that we went into, we walked from one place to Moscow.

862
01:16:03,680 --> 01:16:13,680
And every place we knew place we went into, they'd bring out this huge, round loaf of bread

863
01:16:13,680 --> 01:16:15,680
and salt.

864
01:16:15,680 --> 01:16:19,520
And each person would break bread.

865
01:16:19,520 --> 01:16:27,160
And as we broke bread and ate, shared that bread, we broke barriers.

866
01:16:27,160 --> 01:16:35,360
And while I was there, I began to understand why we were not allowed to eat in restaurants

867
01:16:35,360 --> 01:16:38,600
and would sit with families to eat.

868
01:16:38,600 --> 01:16:42,080
It breaks barriers.

869
01:16:42,080 --> 01:16:45,680
Breaking bread breaks barriers.

870
01:16:45,680 --> 01:16:52,000
And there we broke the barriers and we did not remain strangers or the other.

871
01:16:52,000 --> 01:16:57,640
We were able to really discuss and need and get along.

872
01:16:57,640 --> 01:16:59,640
This very basic, very ancient level.

873
01:16:59,640 --> 01:17:00,640
Yes.

874
01:17:00,640 --> 01:17:13,080
And we talked about the need for peace and to do away with atomic bombs, nuclear weapons.

875
01:17:13,080 --> 01:17:22,680
And while I was there, I was given the Coretta Scott King Award for this book.

876
01:17:22,680 --> 01:17:32,480
And I sent a letter for acceptance in my editor, Reddit.

877
01:17:32,480 --> 01:17:38,520
And that letter said, I had to make a choice.

878
01:17:38,520 --> 01:17:40,920
Did I go on this walk?

879
01:17:40,920 --> 01:17:48,600
Would I stay and go to San Francisco and receive that Honorable Award?

880
01:17:48,600 --> 01:17:54,240
And then I thought about the Coretta Scott King Award.

881
01:17:54,240 --> 01:17:58,280
And what the children would think.

882
01:17:58,280 --> 01:18:05,600
And I thought they would appreciate it if I walked for peace rather than go.

883
01:18:05,600 --> 01:18:16,840
And I made the choice to walk for peace rather than come to the acceptance.

884
01:18:16,840 --> 01:18:22,520
So maybe we can end with this question then connecting to that.

885
01:18:22,520 --> 01:18:29,760
You work in the movement and then we talk about reconciliation and peace.

886
01:18:29,760 --> 01:18:33,280
How do you connect all of these pieces?

887
01:18:34,280 --> 01:18:43,680
I do feel that there can be no peace without justice.

888
01:18:43,680 --> 01:18:50,680
And all of the efforts that we made in the 60s, especially throughout our history,

889
01:18:50,680 --> 01:18:57,800
we didn't just start working for freedom in the 60s.

890
01:18:57,800 --> 01:19:05,080
And it was just not Martin Luther King and Fannie Lou Hamer and Rosa Parks.

891
01:19:05,080 --> 01:19:21,280
It was a lot of young, energetic people and leaders who were killed and who were named and bombed.

892
01:19:21,280 --> 01:19:35,880
So I do feel that these people who can do this and really change are those who can listen,

893
01:19:35,880 --> 01:19:45,040
really know how to listen and listen, not thinking about what they are going to say against

894
01:19:45,040 --> 01:19:46,960
the person who is talking.

895
01:19:46,960 --> 01:20:00,720
But listen and come to an understanding that we are all, we are all one, one.

896
01:20:00,720 --> 01:20:14,480
And that we must work together to bring peace to our own lives, to the lives of others,

897
01:20:14,480 --> 01:20:19,200
to this nation, to the world.

898
01:20:19,200 --> 01:20:28,080
And when we really know this, when we know it, we will do it.

899
01:20:28,080 --> 01:20:32,320
We will do it when we know it.

900
01:20:32,320 --> 01:20:36,680
And all the great thinkers have said that.

901
01:20:36,680 --> 01:20:40,800
When you know a thing, you will do it.

902
01:20:40,800 --> 01:20:45,840
Howard Thurman was one of those, stress that.

903
01:20:45,840 --> 01:20:49,000
Know it and do it.

904
01:20:49,000 --> 01:21:01,240
And I feel that is what has kept me with the faith, to try, to bring about a message that

905
01:21:01,240 --> 01:21:03,520
fits our time.

906
01:21:03,520 --> 01:21:10,080
All down the history, gospels have changed, to fit the time and the need of the people.

907
01:21:10,920 --> 01:21:12,920
And we need that now.

908
01:21:12,920 --> 01:21:15,320
It's ongoing, it's ongoing work.

909
01:21:15,320 --> 01:21:20,760
It's on Christianity is an ongoing, it's ongoing.

910
01:21:20,760 --> 01:21:28,120
It is not steady, it is not to be accepted or rejected.

911
01:21:28,120 --> 01:21:37,440
It is to be carried on, to bring about and serve the needs of our time.

912
01:21:37,440 --> 01:21:45,640
And I think that I wish I was 20 years younger.

913
01:21:45,640 --> 01:21:47,320
But I'm not.

914
01:21:47,320 --> 01:21:55,480
And I feel that my time is not there.

915
01:21:55,480 --> 01:21:57,080
What can I ask how old you are today?

916
01:21:57,080 --> 01:22:07,000
I'm 90 years old, this past September, 1970, over the November, 1970, where I was.

917
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:14,440
And six months, 90 years old and six months.

918
01:22:14,440 --> 01:22:22,920
So you can see I don't have too much, all things being equal.

919
01:22:22,920 --> 01:22:24,920
All things being equal.

920
01:22:24,920 --> 01:22:26,640
Yeah, more books.

921
01:22:26,640 --> 01:22:32,360
I was going to say moving and fighting.

922
01:22:32,360 --> 01:22:39,640
I wish I could get a memoir published, but it's hard now.

923
01:22:39,640 --> 01:22:44,440
They want stuff from celebrities.

924
01:22:44,440 --> 01:22:46,200
But you've done so, so much.

925
01:22:46,200 --> 01:22:50,040
And we're so grateful for sharing the story with us today.

926
01:22:50,040 --> 01:22:55,280
Well, I am so grateful for you to listen to my story.

927
01:22:55,280 --> 01:22:56,360
I am.

928
01:22:56,360 --> 01:22:58,160
I feel blessed.

929
01:22:58,160 --> 01:22:59,880
And I feel honored.

930
01:22:59,880 --> 01:23:00,880
As do we.

931
01:23:00,880 --> 01:23:01,880
Thank you.

932
01:23:02,600 --> 01:23:08,280
Any last thing you'd like to say before we wrap up?

933
01:23:08,280 --> 01:23:10,480
So it's just beautiful.

934
01:23:10,480 --> 01:23:13,800
I would just like to acknowledge my children.

935
01:23:13,800 --> 01:23:15,440
I have two sons.

936
01:23:15,440 --> 01:23:20,680
I had a son to pass away in 2008.

937
01:23:20,680 --> 01:23:30,680
He had worked very hard in the Black Studies Department at California State University, Los Angeles.

938
01:23:30,680 --> 01:23:36,880
And he had done some books for young men.

939
01:23:36,880 --> 01:23:48,640
And I have my younger son is living in Santa Monica, California.

940
01:23:48,640 --> 01:23:56,480
And he works for the City College there.

941
01:23:56,480 --> 01:24:01,280
He did films then.

942
01:24:01,280 --> 01:24:05,880
But I am very proud of my children.

943
01:24:05,880 --> 01:24:14,920
And my grandson, whose children you saw, has been very reliable.

944
01:24:14,920 --> 01:24:21,200
And he takes good care and see to it that I'm okay.

945
01:24:21,200 --> 01:24:24,200
This is why you came back to California to be a good kid.

946
01:24:24,200 --> 01:24:26,440
That's why I came back.

947
01:24:26,440 --> 01:24:36,720
And he invited me along with his wife who met and his children.

948
01:24:36,720 --> 01:24:40,200
So that I feel blessed.

949
01:24:40,200 --> 01:24:45,240
Lots of friends and acquaintances.

950
01:24:45,240 --> 01:24:50,960
Oh, there was one thing I didn't talk about.

951
01:24:50,960 --> 01:24:54,600
In 1970.

952
01:24:54,600 --> 01:25:02,000
I worked with a group of people of color nurses.

953
01:25:02,000 --> 01:25:09,480
And we started that name, people of color, rather than minorities.

954
01:25:09,480 --> 01:25:15,720
We did work in the schools of nurses.

955
01:25:15,720 --> 01:25:23,680
At the time when we were doing this work to bring culture, we wanted to get them to

956
01:25:23,680 --> 01:25:31,680
know and appreciate the cultures of people of color, which would be helpful in making

957
01:25:31,680 --> 01:25:35,640
diagnosis.

958
01:25:35,640 --> 01:25:47,880
At that time when they diagnosed shock, synonyms and inflammation, they used red, white, and

959
01:25:47,880 --> 01:25:50,000
blue.

960
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:57,360
And a lot of us died in shock because we could not turn white.

961
01:25:57,360 --> 01:25:59,600
We could not turn red.

962
01:25:59,600 --> 01:26:02,320
We could not turn blue.

963
01:26:02,320 --> 01:26:06,920
And so we worked on that.

964
01:26:06,920 --> 01:26:12,960
And these nurses gave indications of how to determine that.

965
01:26:12,960 --> 01:26:21,160
And we also, at that time, you could go to visit your people in the hospital between

966
01:26:21,160 --> 01:26:24,560
two and four.

967
01:26:24,560 --> 01:26:28,240
And we couldn't go because we were working.

968
01:26:28,240 --> 01:26:38,480
And then they had one set of one menu and a lot of the food that they gave we didn't

969
01:26:38,480 --> 01:26:39,480
like.

970
01:26:39,480 --> 01:26:46,480
And people of color didn't eat that kind of food.

971
01:26:46,480 --> 01:26:53,440
And there was another thing that we did too.

972
01:26:53,440 --> 01:27:06,840
We had it so that doing transition at one time, you couldn't bring children for the end of

973
01:27:06,840 --> 01:27:08,880
that period.

974
01:27:08,880 --> 01:27:16,720
Now the whole family, we talked about how necessary that was for people of color.

975
01:27:16,720 --> 01:27:25,360
And now anybody, or everybody, when doing transition, they provide a room where you can go and

976
01:27:25,360 --> 01:27:29,840
be with that patient during that period.

977
01:27:29,840 --> 01:27:36,720
Asian people were suffering from dehydration because at one time they would just put ice

978
01:27:36,720 --> 01:27:43,400
water on the table and expect people to drink the ice water.

979
01:27:43,400 --> 01:27:47,200
They didn't drink ice water.

980
01:27:47,200 --> 01:27:51,240
There were so few nurses of Native American.

981
01:27:51,240 --> 01:27:56,480
We couldn't get a statistic.

982
01:27:56,480 --> 01:28:07,340
So now, because of this, we added all of this into the text books for nurses and made

983
01:28:07,340 --> 01:28:09,040
all those changes.

984
01:28:09,040 --> 01:28:22,760
And now we are very pleased that the term, People of Color, is much more common uses than

985
01:28:22,760 --> 01:28:26,120
minorities.

986
01:28:26,120 --> 01:28:32,160
So I did the culture of African Americans.

